[288.143816, "i", "uld be after decrypting rounds 1 and 2\n            # and see if we can find consistent key[2] and key[3]\n            \n            # This is still complex. Let me use a simpler statistical test:\n            # For wrong keys, the decrypted values should look random\n            # For right keys, there should be some structure\n            \n            # Count how many bits are set in the differences\n            total_bits = bin(diff_01_L).count('1') + bin(diff_01_R).count('1')\n            total_bits += bin(diff_02_L).count('1') + bin(diff_02_R).count('1')\n            \n            # For wrong keys, expect about 50% of bits set (random)\n            # For right keys, might have fewer bits set (structure)\n            # This is a weak test but might work\n            \n            # Actually, this won't work well. Let me try yet another approach:\n            # Just try to find key[3] that's consistent\n            \n            # Sample a few key[3] values\n            for seed3 in range(0, 0x10000, 512):  # Sample sparsel"]
